 The dog starts with **12** bones. It chews **3** bones each day for **3** days. To find out how many bones are left, we subtract the number of bones it has chewed from the total number of bones:

\begin{equation}
\text{{Number of bones}} = \text{{Total bones}} - (\text{{Bones chewed per day}} \times \text{{Number of days}})
\end{equation}

In this case:

\begin{equation}
\text{{Number of bones}} = 12 - (3 \times 3) = 12 - 9 = \boxed{\textbf{3}}
\end{equation}

So, the dog has **3** bones left.

